              <p align="left" class="style2"> <strong><a href="http://xml.coverpages.org/ni2004-09-14-a.html">IBM Contributes XML-Based Speech Software to Apache and Eclipse Open </a></strong><a href="http://xml.coverpages.org/ni2004-09-14-a.html"><strong>Source Projects.</strong></a><strong><br>
              </strong><strong>The Cover Pages, September 14, 2004 --</strong> At the SpeechTEK 2004 Conference IBM announced a major contribution of software to open source initiatives at the Apache Software Foundation and the Eclipse Foundation. The new software projects are intended to &quot;spur the availability of speech-enabled applications by making it easier and more attractive for developers to build and add speech recognition capability in a standardized way. Supported by more than 20 key industry players from speech vendors to platform providers, the initiative is aimed at ending the battles over competing, proprietary specifications.&quot; An Eclipse Voice Tools Project will &quot;focus on Voice Application tools in the JSP/J2EE space, based on W3C standards, so that these standards become dominant in voice application development. ...<a href="http://xml.coverpages.org/ni2004-09-14-a.html">Full Story</a></p>
